text: I remember when I was a kid I found a small cross on the ground at a street in my village. For some reason (I think I had read a newspaper article on the topic), I immediately assumed it was a fragment of The True Cross of St. Helena that somehow came to me.

It turned out it was an auspiciously coagulated piece of mud shaped by the net-like pattern at the bottom of my shoe. I looked at the outsole and realized I could make tens of such crosses out of the dried mud, but this one just came out perfect, until it fell apart into dust.

Later, reading Gene Wolfe's Book of The New Sun, I was reminded of this when [SPOILERS] Severian loses The Claw and later, at a rose bush, finds hundreds of Claws, which he realizes are just the thorns of the plant. The one of a kind unimaginable ur-cosmic relic was a rose thorn.

Do you know how in "The Binding of Isaac" all monsters are actually meant to be Isaac in a degenerated form? Like an alternative version of him that had given into some vice or fear? Like the "Monstro" first boss makes it visually very evident, even if the idea was later lost.

That's how Hinduism sees all animals, e.g. pig as man fallen unto gluttony, Muhammad also said something similar about men turned into apes ouf of lack of piety. Evola said this about human erotic love being the "prototype" and animal reproductive sexual instinct its degenerates.

It's why using an animal measure on man falls null and foid unless in an endstate of profound decay. We must guard our human-ness and never fall into the trap of seeing our superior organs as sophisticated versions of a beastial equivalents. We do not suffer any bio-programming.

The reason people say things like "trads are wrong, I slept w/ my gf on the first date and didn't think less of her, etc." is because normies fundamentally conceive of doctrines as magazine "lifestyle tips" instead of objective spiritual operations free of any morality, emotions,

As in these laws do not lead to social success, happiness in life, they may even be ruinous, but their non-human character is precisely what lays their weight. A healthy culture is good because it produces an overlap of the two opposites, making normies' crosses lighter to carry.

More on Binding of Isaac, but its developer required five fans to send a video of themselves "hailing Satan" and pledging their souls for him to release a DLC, which was obvious Millennial psuedo-edge shitlibbery, but an objective ritual participation works in spite of any irony.

E.g. Jokingly signing a legal document is still legally binding. Rites have a non-subjective nature, not related to one's personal formula of knowledge, intent, beliefs, burdens. I will become a Binding of Isaac streamer, if twitter stops hitting the spot one day (it never will).

There is a scene in Cormac McCarthy's "The Road", where the protagonists find a house, where men are kept as livestock in a basement and cannibalized limb by limb by their hosts. They see the masters with their wives and the women are all pregnant. It's a truly disgusting scene.

A cruel environment of hopeless lack of resources, no animals, no fertile land, only maneaters over dwindling slaves, all biomass slowly reducing to zero. And yet fertility forced itself. It's what Evola called the vile cycle of procreation, against the heroic concept of family.

At my village there are packs of wild dogs at the outskirts, where the forest starts. In summer, there are often puppies running around barking, the big dogs hunt field mice, one time they got a sheep. In winter they die and cannibalize each other's corpses. Eden eludes us still.
